Browser/WebRTC mDNS considerations

Modern Chromium/Firefox obfuscate host candidates with random mDNS names. You can re-expose LAN IPs on managed endpoints 
by pushing the Chrome policy WebRtcLocalIpsAllowedUrls (or toggling chrome://flags/#enable-webrtc-hide-local-ips-with-mdns/Edge equivalent) 
so ICE exposes host candidates instead of mDNS; set via HKLM\Software\Policies\Google\Chrome.

When users disable the protection manually (common in WebRTC troubleshooting guides), their browsers start advertising 
plain host candidates again, which you can capture via mDNS or ICE signaling to speed up host discovery.
